fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Therefore, it remains to show that P is a proposition. Without loss of generality, we may assume that we have some h: P. By Corollary , we may fix x:A and prove that 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\cong _{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 is a proposition. Of course, this is a retract of the identification type 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen g
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen f x\right \rparen \mathclose {}
,\epsilon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
=_{\mathsf {fiber}\,f\,
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen fx\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {refl}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
 and so by Lemma  it is enough to prove that the latter is a proposition. In fact, we will deduce this via Lemma  by observing that the fiber of f at fx is contractible: using our assumption h:P and the distributivity of products over sums, we may construct a retraction of f exhibiting f as biinvertible and thus by Corollary  contractible.

Let \mathcal {A} be a path object. Any right-cloven family of path objects \mathcal {B}\colon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\to  \mathsf {PathObj} gives rise to a canonical displayed path object over \mathcal {A} in which:

html:ol.html:li:
for x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 and b:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {B} x\right \rvert \mathclose {}
, the reflexivity datum \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {B}}^{x}{b}\colon  b\approx _{\mathcal {B}}^{\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}}b is given by the component \Phi _{\mathcal {B}}xb\colon  b\approx _{\mathcal {B} x} \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}^*b of the unit law of the given cleaving of \mathcal {B}.

