Let \mathcal {A} be a path object and let B be a type. Given a quasi-inverse function g\colon  B\to  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
, we can restrict the path object \mathcal {A} to a path object structure g^*\mathcal {A} on B as follows:

fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
\begin {aligned}

\mathopen {}\left \lvert g^*\mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
&:\equiv  B\\
 x \approx _{g^*\mathcal {A}} y &:\equiv  gx \approx _{\mathcal {A}} gy\\
 \mathsf {rx}_{g^*\mathcal {A}}x &:\equiv  \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}
\mathopen {}\left \lparen gx\right \rparen \mathclose {}

\end {aligned}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Fixing x:B, we must show that \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:B\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}gx\approx _{\mathcal {A}}gy is a proposition. But this is a retract of  \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:A\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}gx\approx _{\mathcal {A}}y, which is a proposition by the univalence of \mathcal {A}; thus the result follows from the closure of propositions under retracts (Lemma ).
